comment:
Those lyrics, from my understanding, are criticizing billionaires and media's power to dictate our life, then rule the world, and no matter what, they won't lose.

Edit: I know this observation might be contradictory if you consider the video, but let's remember that the Phantom Thieves have a media themselves, looking off their side, it's almost like seeing one part of the media rising by breaking the reputation, so yeah, the song is still talking about them, the difference is that they're not letting "common men die below their boots".

And just to be sure you read it, it's my perspective, I could be getting the wrong idea, if so, let me know in the comments.

comment:
Look, I love this intro, this song and everything about it, and this game with all my heart, but I still cannot understand the lyrics more than any song in Persona 5 without having the actual lyrics on standby. Though, I guess it's a gift as it gives an air of mystery to some extent and if you don't pull up the lyrics yourself, you have to put in the work to understand the meaning behind the lyrics as you have to decode what's being said first.
Lucky my original game disc broke right after this game came out (after the celebration from completing the Kaneshiro palace, so I still had a lot more content to get through) so my sister and I could play through all the new stuff and see this dope intro. God, I love Persona.

The symbolism of Joker and Akechi lying in the crushed, beautiful diamonds, symbolizing the ideal world, while lying in opposite directions, with Joker smiling. comment:
Pretty certain that the new girl's dance in the rain is symbolic, even the choppy feeling of it. Atlus loves to distract fans by putting an overload of information in one segment.


It is noteworthy that she is never shown with the Phantom Thieves, but her umbrella is what releases the diamonds that rain down upon the joyous, celebratory group. She is also shown to have red in a sea of grey. Giving her the spotlight is a callback to the original opening where each character was given his/her own introduction. Even the colour palette and the fact that she's dancing supports this. In this next bit--I may or may not be looking too deeply--the first two who are shown in the rain of diamonds are Joker and Akechi. This could imply a connection between her and these two first and then the other thieves.


Also, a closer look at Joker and Akechi lying down (inverted parallel --> very nice touch considering their roles) shows Joker donning a smile of satisfaction and closed eyes (which indicates trust and acceptance, as lying on his back with his eyes closed is a move that makes him five to ten times more vulnerable). Akechi's face is devoid of any particular emotion. It is peaceful, resting as if all burdens have been erased. Like the face of someone sleeping or of a dead man. Both of them are lying on the ground of diamonds with their arms spread out like crosses. Akechi was already there. He did not fall, he did not move. Joker, however, fell beside him happily. This may foreshadow something dark (as the cross symbolises sacrifice, fellow P5 fans already know about Akechi's situation in the original, and everything appears to be right with the world as Joker willingly plops down next to the other) and/or signify their interconnected role, which the players have already learned about from the last game (again, the parallel yet inverted way they lie on the ground, their slight difference in expression, and the diamonds).


This analysis was rushed and left incomplete. The reason for this is partially due to my stubborn avoidance of spoiling or leading myself to conclusions by using only the intro. I am a slow gamer and have only reached the second palace as of now. Sooo, I give my thanks to anyone who took something from this imperfect analysis. (^.^*)
vid_title: Persona 5 Royal - Official Opening Cinematic Trailer

comment:
P5R is made with the intention that you've already played, or at the very least have heard of, P5 the original. Atlus isn't dumb enough to release a new game using the same theme as the original and its kinda odd to see so many people essentially saying "its too different from the P5".

 If they played off the "mysterious phantom thieves" like the first OP, then it just falls flat. We already know the main cast at this point, the introduction stage is long past gone. Sure the plot may/most likely will differ from the P5 in certain aspects, but the characters archetypes aren't changing. P5R works off of that and shows more of the depth that the game will have between characters. We know who's a part of the team, we know they're going to come together eventually. There isn't a *need* to have them be individuals like in P5 where the status of every character was unknown.

Compare the actual content of the videos. P5 OP has a lot of individual shots with a great amount of attitude for each character (And don't get me wrong its still a fantastic piece of art). But how many scenes do you see of the characters in the same shot or even interacting with each other? Hardly any in comparison. And that was one of the primary complaints of the game. Besides key moments in the plot, the Phantom Thieves never actually did anything that would make you think these people were anything more than casual acquaintances. For a game based on making bonds with people it was oddly the weakest aspect.

P5R is showing that Atlus has fixed that. They are going to be real believable friends (as odd as that sounds). We're going to see how they play off one another, both in real life and as PT's, not just 7 people being Akira's friend with 0 interaction outside of his existence. 

Could it have used a little more attitude like P5? Sure. But I'd rather they play it a little safer like they did here than to overdo it and go straight up edge lord. The line to walk to get an opening like P5 is a thin one, and its already incredibly hard to strike gold once.
vid_title: Persona 5 Royal - Official Opening Cinematic Trailer

comment:
Really not a fan of how Atlus rereleases games with added characters, in that they are not like dlc where it's additional, they always tie it into the main story. It makes it seem they planned it all along, removed an integral character for the first release on purpose, so that you don't get the complete game without buying the second version way down the line. Pretty insidious marketing tactics. Between this, the new Catherine, and p4 golden, it's just a fucking gross way of doing things. Just do normal expansions that add to things, instead of weaving it throughout, and release a complete edition with that, like a normal game company.  It's way too on the nose to be anything but insulting to people who bought their game on release, "oh you bought that, now buy the *real* version"...

At this point no one should buy an Atlus game until the second time they release it. Otherwise you get shafted.

comment:
Everyone is talking about the animations so i‚Äôm gonna talk about the symbolism.

Right of the bat, we have the Phantom Thieves stealing a heart, everyone is here, EXCEPT for Akechi and Kasumi. Kasumi is a new character so her absent is normal. Akechi *SPOILERS* is a traitor, so one would think it would be obvious that he would be excluded, but that brings us to the next montage.

The thieves, including Akechi, is destroying a city, with base ball bats, weapons very much stereotypical of Japanese teenage ruffians or yankees, the thieves destroying the city symbolize their rebellion against society. What noticeable is that unlike the first segment, Akechi is with the gang. My theory is, Akechi isn‚Äôt considered a part of the thieves, hence he have no interest in stealing hearts to change people, but he does rebels against society, much like the thieves, that‚Äôs why he appears during the city‚Äôs destruction but not the stealing of the heart.

comment: When I was at the lowest point in my depression and my will to live was for the most part non existent, I stayed in bed day by day no longer even calling in or responding to work calls. One day my wife brought home this game for me to try and help cheer me up a bit, since she heard so many people liked it and knew it was something I might enjoy. I resonated with game and played it over and over, back to back. I would finish the game and instantly start a new save. I was brought to tears more times than I can count. In the end, I was inspired to get help and take control of my life back. I am ecstatic to pick up the game again once it gets released!

comment:
For anyone saying/complaining about how much color it has or that this isn't "down to earth":

The main goal in persona 5 is to essentially take down people who oppress others. This is symbolized by the phantom theives being these giants with hammers, smashing the dark skyscrapers which represent oppression (and may also representative corporations, might be a stretch :p) and turning them into a flurry of colors, which represents freedom.

tl;dr is that phantom theives smash gloomy buildings and "free" them. Probably the best opening I've seen for something in a while, so fitting

comment:
ok, heres the thing. this op is alright but it doesnt live up to the original. not only is the animation all choppy and the pacing and camera movement all over the place, but there isnt much meaning behind the op. this op just seemed like the phantom thieves having a fun time which isnt really a bad thing; its just not the main focus of the game. the main focus *should* be on them actually being phantom thieves which the show and the start and a little at the end which keeps it from being very memorable. in addition, from a newcomer's perspective, they wouldnt know what the message in the game even is from this op unlike the first op, which is known for its clear symbolism.
this isnt by all means a bad op. although the animation is janky and a bit lazy compared to the first one, it is very eye catching, stylish and its sequences are definitely more ambitious than the first op's, all of which i do appreciate. i just would have hoped for a really amazing looking remake of an already amazing game, the op would have also met the standard.

comment:
P5 Royal's OP feels a lot more like P4 Golden's than the original P5's. Hmm, I wonder why...
...Nah, I'm pretty sure I know: it's because P5 was given the Golden treatment to become P5R. Brighter, more vivid visuals? Check. Replaces most of the original OP's seriousness with playfulness/happiness? Check. Less direct emphasis on the main story? Check. A different song that still fits in with the rest of the soundtrack (original included) while simultaneously giving the new, upgraded title a slightly different tone/identity than its predecessor? Check.
P5R is to P5 as P4G is to P4, and in more ways than just one.
